The paper deals with combinatorial optimization in unknown environments, which is a problem commonly studied in the machine learning community. The use of Thompson Sampling, a popular Bayesian algorithm, suggests that the paper may fall under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper deals with optimization problems in networking, which could fall under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) or systems and control (cs.SY). The use of Lipschitz continuity and suboptimality gaps suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) or information theory (cs.IT).
